The army might leave the camp either to attack a near enemy, or to continue the march.

ln the first case the tents were left standing, the baggage remained in its place, and a'guard was left in charge. This guard might cousist osa detail from each legion, or ol entire legions. The latter would be likely to occur when legions of raw recruits were present. These would natur· ally be left within the walls.†

In case of continuing the march, the camp was abandoned. at the first signal of the bugles (regnum profectionis), the tents were struck ; at the second (vasa conclamaretur), they and the rest os the baggage were packed on the beasts; at the third, the march began. To conceal the departure from the enemy, the signals might be omitted. Still it was deerned a point os military honor to sound them.
